The endangered giant panda population in China has increased to around 1,590, with a focus on protecting the Qinling pandas due to their smaller numbers.
A blood bank has been established to aid in breeding and conservation efforts.
Recent reports indicate that pandas are migrating to restored forest areas, facing threats from blooming bamboo and food shortages.
Efforts to rescue and relocate pandas in danger of starvation are underway.
Conservation measures include setting up nature reserves and increasing forest coverage to support the panda population, with Sichuan province being a key habitat.
